<h2>Variables</h2>
<p>Declare a variable using:</p>
<pre><code class="language-csharp">// type varName = value;
string name = "John";</code></pre>
<p><code>double</code> types will need to be ended with a 'D':</p>
<pre><code class="language-csharp">double myNum = 5.99D;</code></pre>
<p><code>float</code> types will need to be ended with a 'F':</p>
<pre><code class="language-csharp">float myNum = 5.75F;</code></pre>
<p>These are called <strong>literal suffixes</strong>. Use <code>m</code> to create a literal decimal.</p>
<p>They can also represent scientific numbers:</p>
<pre><code class="language-csharp">float f1 = 35e3F;
double d1 = 12E4D;</code></pre>

<h3>Constants</h3>
<p>Declare a constant using:</p>
<pre><code class="language-csharp">const int myNum = 15;</code></pre>
<p>Can't be changed.</p>

<h3>Output a variable</h3>
<p>Output a variable by concatenating to a string:</p>
<pre><code class="language-csharp">string name = "John";
Console.WriteLine("Hello " + name);</code></pre>

<h3>Declare many vars</h3>
<pre><code class="language-csharp">int x = 5, y = 4, z = 3;</code></pre>

<h3>Naming Convention</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Can contain letters, digits, and underscore</li>
    <li>Must begin with lowercase or an underscore</li>
    <li>Should start with a lowercase letter</li>
    <li>Are case sensitive</li>
    <li>Reserved keywords cannot be var names</li>
</ul>

<h3>Casting</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Implicit Casting</strong> (automatically) - converting a smaller type to a larger type size</li>
    <ul>
        <li><code>char</code> -> <code>int</code> -> <code>long</code> -> <code>float</code> -> <code>double</code></li>
    </ul>
    <li><strong>Explicit Casting</strong> (manually) - converting a larger type to a smaller size type</li>
    <ul>
        <li><code>double</code> -> <code>float</code> -> <code>long</code> -> <code>int</code> -> <code>char</code></li>
    </ul>
</ul>

